## Testing standards

This document owns test selection, test structure, assertions, fixture design
and test pruning for compiler work.

It does not define the final validation command. For completion gates, read
`docs/src/docs/codebase/style-guide/validation.bd`.

The primary goal is end-to-end language and artifact correctness. Prefer real
usage patterns and complete Beanstalk snippets over narrow implementation-shaped
tests.

### Default testing preference

Integration tests written in Beanstalk are the default for user-visible language behaviour. They exercise the real compiler path and usually provide the strongest regression coverage.

- Prefer integration coverage for user-visible language behaviour
- Add or update unit tests only where subsystem-local behaviour genuinely benefits from them
- Avoid redundant fixtures that assert the same behaviour in slightly different forms
- Prefer meaningful end-to-end cases over brittle implementation-shaped assertions
- When backend or runtime behaviour matters, strengthen artifact assertions where goldens alone are too vague

### Supporting rules

- Prefer externally observable behaviour over implementation detail.
- Use unit tests for hidden invariants that integration output cannot inspect.
- Use one clear primary test owner per behaviour.
- Do not create multiple fixtures that prove the same contract without a distinct stage or backend reason.
- Prefer realistic end-to-end snippets.
- Tests should remain understandable without reading the implementation first.
- Do not make exact internal layout contractual unless that layout is the invariant.

### Test ownership

[table:
    [th:
        [: **Behavior**]
        [: **Owner**]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Pure data or invariant behavior]
        [: Focused unit test near the owning subsystem]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Compiler-stage invariant]
        [: Stage-local unit test naming the invariant]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Stage-boundary orchestration]
        [: Minimal pipeline/build smoke test]
    ]

    [td:
        [: User-facing language behavior]
        [: Integration case under `tests/cases/`]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Backend artifact behavior]
        [: Backend-specific artifact assertions or contractual goldens]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Side-table or hidden compiler fact]
        [: Focused unit test if external output cannot expose it]
    ]

    [td:
        [: Cross-backend semantic parity]
        [: One integration input with backend-specific assertions]
    ]
]

Each behavior should have one primary owner. Secondary coverage is justified only when it protects a distinct boundary, target, diagnostic lane or internal invariant.

### Test location and module layout

- Tests do not live in production implementation files.
- Module-specific tests belong under the module's test directory, for example:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    src/compiler_frontend/hir/tests/
]

- End-to-end or multi-module Rust harness tests belong under:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    src/compiler_tests/
]

- Language and project integration cases belong under:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    tests/cases/
]

- Test-only utilities should live with the tests that own them.
- Do not create broad shared test utility modules for one or two callers.
- Split cross-stage test support only when actual ownership boundaries justify it.

### Unit tests

Retain unit tests for:

- pure data invariants
- impossible states
- side-table facts
- transfer rules
- backend planning policy not observable from artifacts
- narrow parser or formatter algorithms

Prefer integration tests for user-visible behavior.
Once a subsystem is stable, prune superseded unit tests.
Rewrite obsolete tests rather than preserving old API shapes.
A unit test should name the invariant it protects.
Do not use unit coverage as a substitute for an end-to-end case when user behavior changed.

### Integration cases

- `bean tests` runs the integration test runner.
- Use real Beanstalk snippets.
- Each canonical case is one self-contained scenario directory.
- Keep helper source files inside the owning case's `input/` directory.
- Do not let helper files become unintended standalone cases.
- Add strong output assertions where behavior is visible.
- Prefer top-level templates to simulate output.
- Avoid `io.line(...)` unless console behavior is itself under test.

### Successful backend intent

Every successful HTML and HTML-Wasm backend run applies its universal backend baseline. The
baseline protects harness and target invariants. It is not the case's authored semantic contract.

Use `success_contract = "acceptance_only"` only when that backend has no stronger case-specific
semantic, artifact, golden, absence or expected-warning assertion.

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    [backends.html]
    mode = "success"
    warnings = "forbid"
    success_contract = "acceptance_only"
]

Acceptance-only intent does not disable the baseline. The audit records both
`baseline_applied = true` and `acceptance_only = true`, with `backend_baseline` and
`acceptance_only` in `assertion_kinds`.

Do not combine acceptance-only intent with artifact assertions, golden mode, rendered-output
assertions, artifact-absence assertions or an authored expected-warning contract. A whole case
whose backends are all acceptance-only uses `role = "smoke"`. A mixed-backend case may use a
boundary or backend role when another backend owns a stronger contract.

A successful backend with only the universal baseline is invalid. Typed fixture loading rejects it
before policy evaluation, listing, audit, or execution.

For new type-system syntax, include:

- positive usage
- value/type namespace misuse
- import visibility
- duplicates
- cross-file resolution
- target/backend rejection where relevant

Canonical fixture shape:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    tests/cases/
    ├── manifest.toml
    └── case_name/
        ├── input/
        │   ├── main.bst
        │   └── helper.bst
        ├── expect.toml
        └── golden/
            ├── html/
            └── html_wasm/
]

- `manifest.toml` is the authoritative case order. Every case declares a unique canonical `id`,
  unique fixture `path` and at least one non-empty tag.
- Manifest case paths are relative and may not contain absolute, platform-prefix, parent or
  current-directory components. Canonicalised fixture roots must remain inside `tests/cases/`,
  including through symlinks.
- IDs, paths, tags, contracts, roles and configured entries reject leading or trailing whitespace.
  Tags within one case must be unique.
- `contract` and `role` are optional while classification is being backfilled. Supported roles are
  `primary`, `boundary`, `backend`, `adversarial` and `smoke`.
- A `primary` case requires a contract, and one contract may have at most one primary case.
- Case IDs, tags, contracts and roles are retained as typed runner metadata. Do not reconstruct
  them from display text or fixture paths.
- One case folder owns all inputs and expectations for that scenario.

Manifest entry shape:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    [[case]]
    id = "borrow_conflict_resolved_by_reordering"
    path = "borrow_conflict_resolved_by_reordering"
    tags = ["integration", "borrows"]
    contract = "language.bindings.alias_final_use_allows_mutable_rebinding"
    role = "primary"
]

### Focused integration selection and inventory

Use the canonical case ID and retained metadata for local iteration:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    cargo run --quiet -- tests --case arithmetic_operator_precedence --backend html
    cargo run --quiet -- tests --tag borrows --tag diagnostics --backend html
    cargo run --quiet -- tests --contract <contract-id>
    cargo run --quiet -- tests --list --tag borrows
]

- `--case` and `--contract` are exact matches.
- Repeatable `--tag` filters compose as logical AND.
- Case, tag, contract and backend filters compose and preserve manifest/backend order.
- `--list` accepts selection filters and reports canonical ID, selected backend blocks, tags,
  contract and role without compiling cases.
- Duplicate singleton options, duplicate tag values, missing values, unknown flags and positional
  arguments are errors.

Use the audit mode to validate and inventory the complete canonical suite without compiling cases:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    cargo run --quiet -- tests --audit
]

Audit cannot be combined with filters or `--list`. It writes the reporting-owned JSON inventory to
`target/test-reports/integration_suite_inventory.json`, including canonical metadata, backend
expectation facts, hard-policy violations and advisory missing-classification findings. The report
is review input only; it never deletes, merges or rewrites fixtures.

The schema 6 inventory reports acceptance-only, rendered-output, artifact, golden, absence and
expected-warning backend counts, plus the zero baseline-only invariant. It reports exact, ordered
and exact-once runtime contracts separately. Per-backend fields keep `baseline_applied`,
`acceptance_only`, `assertion_kinds`, `golden_present`, `golden_mode`, every rendered-output form,
exact warning codes, diagnostic match mode and any contains-mode reason separate so the report
matches what ran.

Hard policy has one suite-policy owner. Duplicate primary contracts, a primary without a contract
and a whole-case acceptance-only fixture without `role = "smoke"` are hard findings. Normal list
and execution modes reject hard findings before selection or compilation. Audit still writes the
complete JSON report, then returns failure. Advisory classification findings remain non-fatal.

### Runtime output assertions

Runtime assertions use one Node harness. It records console output and HTML fragment inserts in one
event array when each event happens, then joins their text with newlines in that same order. Channel
views are derived from the event array. They never reconstruct chronology after execution.

The harness runs only when a backend declares a rendered-output assertion. It executes the emitted
page scripts and waits for one documented microtask tick so scheduled reactive updates can flush.
Do not make extra scheduler turns or incidental microtask counts contractual.

Choose the narrowest field that owns the behaviour:

- `rendered_output_exact` protects the complete combined output. It is mutually exclusive with the
  other rendered-output fields. Exact comparison normalizes line endings only and preserves every
  other whitespace difference.
- `rendered_output_contains_in_order` protects the relative order of two or more fragments.
- `rendered_output_contains_exactly_once` protects activation, mounting and helper output from
  duplication.
- `rendered_output_contains` and `rendered_output_not_contains` protect required and forbidden
  fragments when complete output isn't the contract.

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    [backends.html]
    mode = "success"
    warnings = "forbid"
    rendered_output_contains = ["active-root"]
    rendered_output_not_contains = ["imported-root"]
    rendered_output_contains_in_order = ["before-loop", "after-loop"]
    rendered_output_contains_exactly_once = ["active-root", "mounted"]
]

Use exact output for small deterministic behaviours such as loop or map operation results. Use
ordered and exact-once fragments when unrelated output may coexist. Prefer these runtime contracts
over generated JavaScript text or a whole-page golden when execution is the real owner.

### Diagnostics assertions

- Ordinary source/config/import/type/rule/borrow failures should assert stable `diagnostic_codes`.
- `diagnostic_codes` is an exact unordered multiset by default. Repeat a code when the diagnostic
  must occur more than once.
- Add rendered message fragments only when wording or rendered labels are part of the contract.
- Infrastructure-boundary tests may assert infrastructure `ErrorType`.
- Preserve source location assertions where location behavior is important.
- Do not use full rendered diagnostic snapshots when a stable code and structured assertion are sufficient.
- Do not weaken a diagnostic case into a generic "must fail" assertion.

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    [backends.html]
    mode = "failure"
    warnings = "forbid"
    diagnostic_codes = ["BST-RULE-0033", "BST-RULE-0033"]
]

Use `diagnostic_assertions` when a broad code needs a compiler-owned reason or when source
remapping is part of the contract. Each table selects one diagnostic by stable code and one-based
occurrence. A unique code may omit `occurrence`. Repeat the code in `diagnostic_codes` to preserve
its exact multiplicity.

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    [[backends.html.diagnostic_assertions]]
    code = "BST-RULE-0057"
    reason = "invalid_generic_instantiation.recursive_function_instantiation"
    path = "input/#page.bst"
    line = 3
    count = 1

    [[backends.html.diagnostic_assertions.secondary_labels]]
    occurrence = 1
    path = "input/helpers.bst"
    line = 2
]

- Reason keys come from the compiler payload identity. The runner must not invent a parallel
  reason taxonomy or derive identity from rendered text.
- Paths are normalized relative to the owning fixture and lines are one-based display lines.
- Assert columns only when exact token-span precision is the contract.
- A secondary-label occurrence is one-based among that diagnostic's secondary labels in emitted
  order. Assert only the labels whose location or ordering is the behaviour owner.
- Keep `message_contains` only when rendered wording or label prose is itself contractual.

Use `diagnostic_match = "contains"` only when intentional independent recovery or cascades make
additional diagnostics part of the accepted current behaviour. Every contains-mode block needs a
substantive `diagnostic_match_reason`. The suite audit reports the reason and treats a missing or
blank reason as a hard policy finding.

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    diagnostic_match = "contains"
    diagnostic_match_reason = "Independent recovery may emit additional diagnostics from another source unit."
]

Warnings use a separate backend-local contract:

- `warnings = "forbid"` rejects every warning and accepts no `warning_codes` field.
- `warnings = "ignore"` deliberately makes warnings non-contractual and accepts no
  `warning_codes` field.
- `warnings = "exact"` requires `warning_codes` as an exact unordered multiset. Repeat duplicate
  codes to preserve their required count.

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    [backends.html]
    mode = "success"
    warnings = "exact"
    warning_codes = ["BST-RULE-0022", "BST-RULE-0022"]
    rendered_output_contains = ["warning-contract result=one"]
]

### Backend matrices and artifact assertions

Use one `expect.toml` per case with backend-specific assertion blocks.

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    entry = "."

    [backends.html]
    mode = "success"
    warnings = "forbid"
    artifacts_must_not_exist = ["unexpected.html"]

    [backends.html_wasm]
    mode = "success"
    warnings = "forbid"

    [[backends.html_wasm.artifact_assertions]]
    path = "page.wasm"
    kind = "wasm"
    validate_wasm = true
    must_export = ["memory", "bst_str_ptr", "bst_str_len", "bst_release"]
]

- Use backend-specific blocks within one case.
- `entry = "."` is the one supported current-directory sentinel and selects the case's `input/`
  directory. Every other entry is a relative contained path with no absolute, platform-prefix,
  parent or current-directory component. Its canonical path must remain inside the owning
  `input/` directory, including through symlinks.
- Store strict goldens in:

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    golden/<backend>/
]

- Use artifact assertions for structure: file presence, Wasm validity, exports, imports, expected snippets, absence of forbidden output.
- Use `artifacts_must_not_exist` for success cases whose contract requires an exact normalized output path to be absent. Paths reported as `NotBuilt` are ignored because they were never emitted.
- Use strict goldens only where exact emitted text is contractual.
- The canonical suite currently has no file-backed golden blocks. A future golden needs an explicit
  exact-artifact rationale that a runtime or narrow artifact assertion cannot express.
- Golden discovery recursively counts actual files. Empty or directory-only golden trees do not
  create a contract. Nested files do.
- `golden_mode` without at least one discovered file is invalid. When files exist, strict is the
  default if no mode is authored. When no files exist, audit reports `golden_present = false` and
  `golden_mode = null`.
- Prefer semantic or rendered-output assertions for behavior-first cases.
- Strengthen artifact assertions when a golden can pass while structural behavior is wrong.
- Do not require unsupported backends to succeed merely for matrix symmetry. Assert the intended rejection contract.

### HIR and internal-IR assertions

- Assert semantic relationships rather than incidental indexes.
- Prefer branch joins, merge-local relationships, jump arguments, region ownership, side-table keys, stable call targets and required operation kinds.
- Avoid exact block IDs or vector offsets unless exact layout is the invariant.
- Do not make temporary lowering order part of the public test contract.
- For HIR validation, distinguish malformed-HIR invariant tests from user-facing source diagnostic tests.

### Fixtures and temporary files

- Prefer `tempfile::tempdir()` for temporary directories and files.
- Use unmanaged paths only when the test intentionally owns cleanup.
- Keep fixtures local to their owner.
- Do not commit generated `dev/` or `release/` outputs from test or benchmark projects.
- Avoid shared fixture builders that hide important source shape.

### Pruning and duplicate coverage

- Remove tests tied only to deleted implementation paths.
- Avoid several fixtures that differ only cosmetically.
- Preserve duplicates only when they protect different stages, diagnostic reasons, backends, source locations or artifact contracts.
- Localize one-caller fixtures.
- When two tests overlap, identify the primary owner and either merge them, narrow each to a distinct invariant or delete the weaker one.
- Do not preserve obsolete fixtures for historical compatibility.

### Benchmarks are not correctness tests

Benchmark fixtures are performance evidence, not correctness coverage.

Do not use benchmark coverage as a substitute for unit or integration tests.
Negative diagnostics belong in `tests/cases`, not benchmark fixtures.

Use `bench-check` to detect broad performance regressions after correctness has
already been established by ordinary tests.

### Testing checklist

Before considering test coverage complete, check:

- The behavior has one clear primary test owner.
- User-visible behavior has end-to-end integration coverage.
- Internal-only invariants have focused unit coverage where needed.
- Failure cases assert stable diagnostic codes.
- Rendered text is asserted only when it is contractual.
- Backend behavior uses the narrowest useful artifact assertions.
- Goldens are used only where exact output is a contract.
- HIR tests avoid incidental block and local numbering.
- Multi-file fixtures remain inside one case directory.
- Temporary files use owned cleanup.
- No benchmark fixture is being used as a correctness substitute.
- Redundant or obsolete coverage has been removed.
